        "---\n",
        "## Part 7 | Summary & Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "**ARIMA**, short-run serial dependence in yield changes and produces a point forecast. For Treasury yields the series is close to a random walk so the point forecast is usually close to the last observation\n",
        "\n",
        "**GARCH**, time-varying vol. The confidence bands expand when current volatility is elevated and contract when things are calm. That's a much more realistic picture of forecast uncertainty than a constant-width band.\n",
        "\n",
        "**it ignores:** macro data (CPI, NFP, Fed meetings), term structure dynamics across the whole curve, and structural breaks across rate regimes. The 2022 hiking cycle is a different regime from 2015–2019 , parameters estimated over both will be averaged and probably wrong for either.\n",
        "\n",
        "**can do**\n",
        "- VAR — model 2Y, 5Y, 10Y jointly as a system\n",
        "- Nelson-Siegel — parametric curve model, used by central banks\n",
        "- ARIMAX — add macro variables as exogenous regressors\n",
        "- Regime-switching GARCH — separate high/low vol regimes explicitly"
      ]
